ectively?\n\nCONCEPT TO REVIEW:\n- Take a moment to revisit how integer division and the modulus operator work in Python, as they can be quite useful in this context.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\n- Keep experimenting and refining your code; every step you take is a step toward becoming a better programmer!','2026-03-01 15:46:08',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL),(22,2,'N/A','def min_coins(amount):\r\n    denominations = [2000, 500, 200, 100, 50, 20, 10, 5, 2, 1]\r\n    count = 0\r\n\r\n    for coin in denominations:\r\n        if amount >= coin:\r\n            num = amount // coin\r\n            count += num\r\n            amount -= num * coin\r\n            print(coin, \":\", num)\r\n\r\n    print(\"Total coins/notes:\", count)\r\n\r\nmin_coins(2758)','WHAT YOU\'RE DOING WELL:\n- Your approach to using a list of denominations and iterating through them is a solid strategy for solving the coin change problem. It\'s great to see you implementing logical steps to minimize the number of coins!\n\nTHINGS TO RETHINK:\n- Consider how the code behaves when the amount is exactly zero or when it’s less than the smallest denomination. Also, think about whether you are accounting for all possible scenarios in your calculations.\n\nGUIDED QUESTIONS:\n1. What happens to the `amount` if it is less than the smallest denomination in your list?\n2. How would you handle a situation where the amount is not a whole number?\n\nCONCEPT TO REVIEW:\n- Review how integer division (`//`) works in Python and how it relates to the problem of counting coins.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\n- Keep experimenting with your code; every small step you take in understanding will lead to greater mastery of programming!','2026-03-01 15:46:11',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,NULL),(23,2,'N/A','a = 2\r\nif a == 2:\r\n    print(\'yes\')\r\nelse:\r\n    print(\'no\')','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- The code is straightforward and easy to understand.\n- Proper use of conditional statements to check the value of `a`.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- The code correctly check