nation is used.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- The code works by iterating through a predefined list of denominations, starting from the largest. For each denomination, it calculates how many of that coin can fit into the remaining amount, updates the count of coins, and reduces the amount accordingly. This ensures that the fewest coins are used to make up the total.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n10/10  \nReason: The implementation is efficient, clear, and achieves the desired outcome without any errors.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\n- Great job on crafting a solution that is both effective and easy to understand! Keep up the fantastic work!','2026-03-13 05:52:51','CORRECT',95,0,1,85),(45,4,'N/A','def min_coins(coins, amount):\r\n    coins.sort(reverse=True)   # sort coins in descending order\r\n    result = []\r\n\r\n    for coin in coins:\r\n        while amount >= coin:\r\n            amount -= coin\r\n            result.append(coin)\r\n\r\n    return result\r\n\r\n\r\ncoins = [1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100]\r\namount = 93\r\n\r\nused_coins = min_coins(coins, amount)\r\n\r\nprint(\"Coins used:\", used_coins)\r\nprint(\"Number of coins:\", len(used_coins))','THINGS TO RETHINK:\n- The current approach may not guarantee the minimum number of coins used for certain amounts, especially when larger denominations are involved.\n\nCONCEPTS TO REVIEW:\n- Greedy algorithms and their limitations.\n- Dynamic programming for coin change problems.\n\nGUIDING QUESTIONS:\n- How does the order of coin selection affect the total number of coins used?\n- Can you think of a scenario where using a larger coin first might lead to a suboptimal solution?\n- What alternative strategies could you implement to ensure the minimum number of coins is used?\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n5/10  \nReason: The code works for some cases but fails to guarantee the optimal solution in all scenarios.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nKeep pushing through the challenges; every step you take brings you closer to mastering coding!','2026-03-13 09:52:09','INCORRECT',9