 logic is correct, clear, and efficient; only minor improvements (like input validation or clearer naming/comments) could make it even more robust and readable.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re thinking about the problem in exactly the right way—keep building on this clear, step-by-step reasoning style.','2026-03-29 05:48:01','CORRECT',92,0,1,82),(77,3,'N/A','def minRemovals(N, B, S):\r\n    \r\n    # Compute prefix drain for each position\r\n    battery = B\r\n    fail_at = -1\r\n    \r\n    for i in range(N):\r\n        if S[i] == \'H\':\r\n            battery -= 2\r\n        else:\r\n            battery -= 1\r\n        if battery < 0:\r\n            fail_at = i\r\n            break\r\n    \r\n    # If never fails, remove nothing\r\n    if fail_at == -1:\r\n        return 0\r\n    \r\n    # Must remove tasks from end until sequence up to fail_at works\r\n    # Remove all tasks from fail_at onwards\r\n    return N - fail_at','THINGS TO RETHINK:\n- Assuming that removing tasks must always be from the end rather than considering removals anywhere in the sequence.\n- Only checking the first failure point once and not recomputing battery after hypothetical removals.\n- Treating all removals as a single contiguous suffix instead of exploring minimal subsets of tasks to remove.\n- Not considering that removing earlier “H” tasks might be more beneficial than removing later “L” tasks.\n- Lack of handling for edge cases (e.g., very small B, all \'H\', all \'L\', or alternating patterns).\n\nCONCEPTS TO REVIEW:\n- Greedy algorithms and when they are/aren’t optimal.\n- Prefix sums / running totals and how to recompute them after changes.\n- Optimization problems involving removals or subsequences (e.g., “minimum deletions to satisfy constraint”).\n- Time complexity trade-offs when trying all possibilities vs. using a smarter strategy.\n- Problem modeling: turning “battery never negative” into a constraint on partial sums.\n\nGUIDING QUESTIONS:\n- If you could remove tasks from *any*