ks can be completed with the given battery by subtracting 2 for \'H\' and 1 otherwise, returning False as soon as battery < 0.\n- The binary search over `remove_count` (from 0 to n) finds the smallest number of tasks to remove such that `is_possible(remove_count)` is True.\n- The invariant is: for any `k` where `is_possible(k)` is True, all larger `k\' > k` will also be True (since fewer tasks are executed), which makes the search space monotonic and valid for binary search.\n- The loop narrows `[left, right)` until `left` is the minimal feasible removal count, which is then returned.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: The algorithm is logically sound, efficient (O(n log n)), and clearly structured; minor improvements could be made in naming and documentation for even better clarity.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re doing a great job structuring efficient solutions—keep pushing, you’re very close to writing production-quality code consistently.','2026-03-30 07:03:16','CORRECT',92,0,0,68),(100,4,'N/A','a = 5\r\nb = 6\r\n#to find area of rectangle\r\nprint(\"area of rectangle is:\")\r\nprint(a*b)','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Correct use of variables to store dimensions.\n- Clear, helpful comment explaining the purpose of the code.\n- Simple and direct calculation of the rectangle’s area.\n- Output is easy to read and understand.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- The area of a rectangle is length × breadth; here `a` and `b` store those values (5 and 6), and `a*b` correctly computes 30, which is then printed.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Logically correct, clear, and readable; could be slightly improved with more descriptive variable names or formatted output.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\n- You’re building a solid foundation—keep experimenting and adding small improvements to your code!','2026-04-09 14:23:48','CORRECT',98,0,0,10),(101,4,'N/A','a = 5\r\nb = 6\r\nprint(\"area of rectangle is:\")\r\nprint(a*b)','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Correctly assigns side lengths to variables and uses them in the calcul