 DONE WELL:\n- Uses a clear, ordered list of denominations that matches a standard currency system.\n- Greedy approach is implemented cleanly with integer division and subtraction.\n- Tracks both per-denomination usage and total count in an easy-to-read way.\n- Code is short, readable, and logically structured with a simple loop.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- The denominations are sorted from largest to smallest, which is essential for the greedy strategy.\n- For each coin, `amount // coin` finds the maximum number of that denomination that can fit into the remaining amount.\n- Subtracting `num * coin` from `amount` ensures the remainder is always less than the current coin, so the algorithm progresses correctly to smaller coins.\n- Because this denomination set is canonical (like standard currency), the greedy method guarantees the minimum number of coins/notes.\n- The loop ends when all denominations are processed, and the remaining amount is zero, so the total count is minimal and correct.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Correct, efficient, and readable; could be slightly improved by returning values instead of only printing and by separating logic from I/O.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re building a solid foundation—keep experimenting with small improvements like returning data structures and you’ll level up quickly.','2026-04-09 14:27:04','CORRECT',96,0,0,48),(104,4,'N/A','# Node class\r\nclass Node:\r\n    def __init__(self, data):\r\n        self.data = data\r\n        self.next = None\r\n\r\n\r\n# Linked List class\r\nclass LinkedList:\r\n    def __init__(self):\r\n        self.head = None\r\n\r\n    # Insert at beginning\r\n    def insert_beginning(self, data):\r\n        new_node = Node(data)\r\n        new_node.next = self.head\r\n        self.head = new_node\r\n\r\n    # Insert at end\r\n    def insert_end(self, data):\r\n        new_node = Node(data)\r\n\r\n        if self.head is None:\r\n            self.head = new_node\r\n            return\r\n\r\n        temp = self.head\r\n        while temp.next:\r\n            temp = temp.next\r\n\r\n        temp.next = new_node\r\n\r\n    # Display linked list\r\n    def display(self):\r\n        temp = self.head\r\n        while temp:\r\n            print(temp.data, end=\" -> \")\r\n            temp = temp.next\r\n        print(\"None\")\r\n\r\n\r\n# Creating linked list\r\nll = LinkedList()\r\n\r\nll.insert_beginning(10)\r\nll.insert_beginning(5)\r\nll.insert_end(20)\r\nll.insert_end(30)\r\n\r\nprint(\"Linked List:\")\r\nll.display()','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Clean, readable class design separating `Node` and `LinkedList`.\n- Correct pointer handling in both `insert_beginning` and `insert_end`.\n- Proper handling of the empty-list case in `insert_end`.\n- Simple, effective `display` method that clearly shows list structure.\n- Good example usage that demonstrates both insertion methods.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- `insert_beginning` creates a new node, points its `next` to the current head, then updates `head` to the new node, so the new node becomes the first element.\n- `insert_end` traverses from `head` until it finds the last node (`temp.next` is `None`), then sets that node’s `next` to the new node, correctly appending it.\n- When the list is empty (`head is None`), `insert_end` directly sets `head` to the new node, ensuring the first element is added correctly.\n- `display` walks the list from `head` following `next` pointers until `None`, printing each `data`, which confirms the list’s order and structure.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Correct, clear, and well-structured implementation; could be enhanced with minor extras like docstrings or edge-case tests, but the core logic is solid.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re building a strong foundation—keep experimenting with more operations like deletion and search to grow your confidence.','2026-04-09 14:28:06','CORRECT',98,0,0,45),(105,4,'N/A','\r\nclass Node:\r\n    def __init__(self, data):\r\n        self.data = data\r\n        self.ne