me-checking logic using the square root optimization.\n- Proper handling of edge cases (numbers ≤ 1).\n- Clean separation of logic (`is_prime_number`) and user interaction (`main`).\n- Standard Python entry-point pattern (`if __name__ == \"__main__\":`) is used correctly.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- Numbers less than or equal to 1 are not prime, so the function immediately returns `False` for them.\n- For numbers greater than 1, the loop checks divisibility from 2 up to `sqrt(number)` because if a number has a factor larger than its square root, the corresponding paired factor must be smaller than the square root and would already have been found.\n- If any divisor evenly divides the number (`number % i == 0`), the function returns `False`, meaning the number is composite.\n- If no divisors are found in that range, the function returns `True`, meaning the number is prime.\n- The `main` function gets user input, converts it to an integer, and uses `is_prime_number` to decide which message to print, correctly wiring the logic to the user interface.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Correct, efficient, and cleanly structured; could be improved slightly with input validation or more user-friendly error handling.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re doing a great job—keep building on this solid foundation and your coding skills will grow quickly.','2026-04-09 14:33:16','CORRECT',100,0,0,50),(109,4,'N/A','def calculate_sum_of_numbers(numbers_list):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    This function takes a list of numbers as input\r\n    and returns the sum of all elements in the list.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    total_sum = 0\r\n    \r\n    for index in range(len(numbers_list)):\r\n        total_sum = total_sum + numbers_list[index]\r\n    \r\n    return total_sum\r\n\r\n\r\ndef main():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Main function to execute the program.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    user_input = input(\"Enter numbers separated by space: \")\r\n    numbers = list(map(int, user_input.split()))\r\n    \r\n    result = calculate_s