"\"\"\r\n        total_sum = 0\r\n\r\n        for index, value in enumerate(self.numbers):\r\n            total_sum = total_sum + value\r\n\r\n        return total_sum\r\n\r\n\r\ndef parse_input(input_string):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Converts a space-separated string into a list of integers.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    return list(map(int, input_string.strip().split()))\r\n\r\n\r\ndef display_result(result):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Displays the computed result in a formatted manner.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    print(f\"The computed sum of the provided numbers is: {result}\")\r\n\r\n\r\ndef main():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Main execution function orchestrating input, processing, and output.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    raw_input_data = input(\"Enter numbers separated by spaces: \")\r\n    processed_numbers = parse_input(raw_input_data)\r\n\r\n    processor = NumberProcessor(processed_numbers)\r\n    result = processor.compute_sum()\r\n\r\n    display_result(result)\r\n\r\n\r\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\r\n    main()','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Clear, descriptive docstrings and function names that make the code easy to understand.\n- Good separation of concerns: input parsing, processing, and output are in distinct functions/classes.\n- Use of a `NumberProcessor` class makes the logic extensible for future numeric operations.\n- `parse_input` is concise and uses Python’s built-in functions effectively.\n- The `main()` guard (`if __name__ == \"__main__\":`) is correctly used for script execution.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- `parse_input` trims the input string, splits it by spaces, and converts each token to an integer, producing a list of integers.\n- `NumberProcessor` stores this list and `compute_sum` iterates through it, accumulating the total in `total_sum`.\n- The `for index, value in enumerate(self.numbers)` loop visits every element exactly once and adds it to `total_sum`, so the final value is the sum of all numbers.\n- `main()` coordinates the flow: it reads user input, parses it into integers, passes them to `NumberProcessor`, computes the sum, and then prints the result via `display_result`.\n- Because each step is deterministic and correctly implemented, the program reliably outputs the correct sum for any valid integer input.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Clean, readable, and logically sound structure with good separation of concerns; could be slightly improved with minor Pythonic refinements (e.g., using `sum(self.numbers)` or basic input validation).\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re building a solid foundation—keep writing code this clear and you’ll level up very quickly.','2026-04-09 14:34:45','CORRECT',98,0,0,68),(111,4,'N/A','def check_even_or_odd(number):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Determines whether the provided integer is even or odd.\r\n    An even number is divisible by 2 without remainder.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    if number % 2 == 0:\r\n        return \"Even\"\r\n    else:\r\n        return \"Odd\"\r\n\r\n\r\ndef main():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Entry point of the program.\r\n    Responsible for handling user interaction.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    try:\r\n        user_input = input(\"Please enter an integer value: \")\r\n        converted_number = int(user_input)\r\n\r\n        result = check_even_or_odd(converted_number)\r\n\r\n        print(f\"The number {converted_number} is classified as: {result}\")\r\n\r\n    except ValueError:\r\n        print(\"Invalid input detected. Please enter a valid integer.\")\r\n\r\n\r\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\r\n    main()','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Clear, descriptive function and variable names (`check_even_or_odd`, `converted_number`, `user_input`).\n- Helpful docstrings that explain purpose and behavior.\n- Proper use of `if __name__ == \"__main__\":` to define the program entry point.\n- Good separation of concerns: logic in `check_even_or_odd`, interaction in `main`.\n- Robust input handling with `try/except` to catch invalid user input.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- The function `check_even_or_odd` uses the modulo operator `%` to check the remainder when dividing by 2; if `number % 2 == 0`, the number is even, otherwise it’s odd—this matches the mathematical definition.\n- `main()` reads input as a string, attempts to convert it to an integer with `int(user_input)`, and only proceeds if conversion succeeds.\n- On success, it passes the integer to `check_even_or_odd`, receives either `\"Even\"` or `\"Odd\"`, and prints a formatted message including both the number and its classification.\n- If conversion fails (e.g., user types \"abc\"), a `ValueError` is raised and caught, triggering a clear error message instead of crashing the program.\n- The `if __name__ == \"__main__\": main()` guard ensures the script only runs `main()` when executed directly, not when imported as a module.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Clean, readable, and logically sound with proper error handling; could be slightly improved with minor enhancements like type hints or more specific messaging, but it’s already strong.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re building solid habits with structure, naming, and error handling—keep going, you’re on a great path.','2026-04-09 14:35:15','CORRECT',100,0,0,65),(112,4,'N/A','class FactorialCalculator:\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    A class responsible for computing the factorial of a given non-negative integer.\r\n    \r\n    The factorial of a number n is defined as:\r\n    n! = n × (n-1) × (n-2) × ... × 1\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n\r\n    def __init__(self, number):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Initializes the FactorialCalculator with the provided number.\r\n\r\n        :param number: Integer for which factorial is to be calculated\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        self.number = number\r\n\r\n    def validate_input(self):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Validates that the number is a non-negative integer.\r\n\r\n        :raises ValueError: If the input is invalid\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        if not isinstance(self.number, int):\r\n            raise ValueError(\"Input must be an integer.\")\r\n        if self.number < 0:\r\n            raise ValueError(\"Factorial is not defined for negative numbers.\")\r\n\r\n    def compute_factorial(self):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Computes the factorial of the stored number.\r\n\r\n        :return: Factorial of the number\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        self.validate_input()\r\n\r\n        result = 1\r\n\r\n        for current_value in range(1, self.number + 1):\r\n            result = result * current_value\r\n\r\n        return result\r\n\r\n\r\ndef get_user_input():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Handles user input and converts it into an integer.\r\n\r\n    :return: Integer input from user\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    raw_input_value = input(\"Please enter a non-negative integer: \")\r\n\r\n    try:\r\n        converted_value = int(raw_input_value)\r\n        return converted_value\r\n    except ValueError:\r\n        raise ValueError(\"Invalid input. Please enter a valid integer.\")\r\n\r\n\r\ndef display_output(number, factorial_result):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Displays the computed factorial in a formatted manner.\r\n\r\n    :param number: Input number\r\n    :param factorial_result: Computed factorial result\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    print(f\"The factorial of {number} is: {factorial_result}\")\r\n\r\n\r\ndef main():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Main execution function that coordinates the program flow.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    try:\r\n        user_number = get_user_input()\r\n\r\n        calculator = FactorialCalculator(user_number)\r\n        result = calculator.compute_factorial()\r\n\r\n        display_output(user_number, result)\r\n\r\n    except ValueError as error:\r\n        print(f\"Error: {error}\")\r\n\r\n\r\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\r\n    main()','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Clear separation of concerns with dedicated functions for input, processing, and output.\n- Good use of a class (`FactorialCalculator`) to encapsulate factorial logic and validation.\n- Input validation is explicit and uses informative error messages.\n- Docstrings are present and descriptive, improving readability and maintainability.\n- The iterative factorial implementation is straightforward and easy to follow.\n- The `main` guard (`if __name__ == \"__main__\":`) is correctly used for script execution.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- `get_user_input` reads a string, attempts to convert it to `int`, and raises a `ValueError` if conversion fails, ensuring only integers proceed.\n- `FactorialCalculator.__init__` stores the number; `validate_input` ensures it is an `int` and non-negative, which matches the mathematical domain of factorial.\n- `compute_factorial` calls `validate_input` first, then initializes `result` to 1 and multiplies it by each integer from 1 to `number` inclusive, which matches the definition of n!; for 0, the loop doesn’t run and returns 1, which is correct.\n- `main` orchestrates the flow: gets input, constructs the calculator, computes the factorial, and displays it; any `ValueError` raised along the way is caught and printed, preventing crashes and giving user feedback.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: Clean, logically correct, well-structured, and well-documented; could be slightly improved with minor enhancements (e.g., type hints, more robust input loop) but is already strong.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re structuring your code like a professional—keep building on this solid foundation.','2026-04-09 14:36:22','CORRECT',98,0,0,65),(113,4,'N/A','class DigitSummationProcessor:\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    The DigitSummationProcessor class is designed to encapsulate\r\n    all functionality required to compute the sum of digits of a given integer.\r\n    \r\n    This implementation follows a structured and modular approach\r\n    to ensure clarity, maintainability, and extensibility.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n\r\n    def __init__(self, input_number):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Initializes the processor with the provided integer value.\r\n\r\n        :param input_number: The integer whose digits are to be summed\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        self.input_number = input_number\r\n\r\n    def validate_input_number(self):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Validates that the provided input is an integer and is non-negative.\r\n\r\n        :raises ValueError: If validation fails\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        if not isinstance(self.input_number, int):\r\n            raise ValueError(\"The provided input must be of type integer.\")\r\n\r\n        if self.input_number < 0:\r\n            raise ValueError(\"The provided integer must be non-negative.\")\r\n\r\n    def convert_number_to_string(self):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Converts the integer into its string representation.\r\n\r\n        :return: String representation of the integer\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        return str(self.input_number)\r\n\r\n    def compute_sum_of_digits(self):\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        Computes the sum of digits of the stored integer.\r\n\r\n        :return: Integer representing the sum of digits\r\n        \"\"\"\r\n        self.validate_input_number()\r\n\r\n        string_representation = self.convert_number_to_string()\r\n\r\n        cumulative_sum = 0\r\n\r\n        for character_index in range(len(string_representation)):\r\n            current_character = string_representation[character_index]\r\n            numeric_value = int(current_character)\r\n            cumulative_sum = cumulative_sum + numeric_value\r\n\r\n        return cumulative_sum\r\n\r\n\r\ndef retrieve_user_input():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Responsible for retrieving input from the user and converting it into an integer.\r\n\r\n    :return: Integer provided by the user\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    raw_user_input = input(\"Please enter a non-negative integer value: \")\r\n\r\n    try:\r\n        processed_input = int(raw_user_input)\r\n        return processed_input\r\n    except ValueError:\r\n        raise ValueError(\"Invalid input encountered. Expected an integer value.\")\r\n\r\n\r\ndef present_output(original_number, computed_result):\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Presents the computed result to the user in a structured format.\r\n\r\n    :param original_number: The original number provided by the user\r\n    :param computed_result: The computed sum of digits\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    print(\"========================================\")\r\n    print(f\"Input Number           : {original_number}\")\r\n    print(f\"Sum of Digits Computed : {computed_result}\")\r\n    print(\"========================================\")\r\n\r\n\r\ndef orchestrate_program_execution():\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    Coordinates the complete execution flow of the program,\r\n    including input retrieval, processing, and output presentation.\r\n    \"\"\"\r\n    try:\r\n        user_provided_number = retrieve_user_input()\r\n\r\n        processor_instance = DigitSummationProcessor(user_provided_number)\r\n\r\n        result_of_computation = processor_instance.compute_sum_of_digits()\r\n\r\n        present_output(user_provided_number, result_of_computation)\r\n\r\n    except ValueError as encountered_error:\r\n        print(f\"Execution Error: {encountered_error}\")\r\n\r\n\r\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\r\n    orchestrate_program_execution()','THINGS DONE WELL:\n- Very clear separation of concerns: input, processing, and output are nicely modularized.\n- Excellent use of docstrings and descriptive names, making the code highly readable and self-explanatory.\n- Input validation is explicit and centralized in `validate_input_number`, improving robustness.\n- The main orchestration function cleanly expresses the program’s flow and handles errors gracefully.\n\nLOGICAL ANALYSIS:\n- `retrieve_user_input` reads a string from the user and attempts to convert it to an integer; if conversion fails, it raises a `ValueError`, ensuring only integers proceed.\n- `DigitSummationProcessor` stores this integer and `validate_input_number` guarantees it is both an `int` and non-negative, preventing invalid states.\n- `convert_number_to_string` turns the integer into its string form, so each digit can be processed individually.\n- In `compute_sum_of_digits`, the loop iterates over each character in the string representation, converts each character back to an integer digit, and accumulates the total in `cumulative_sum`.\n- Because the string representation of a non-negative integer consists only of digit characters, `int(current_character)` is always valid, and the final `cumulative_sum` is exactly the sum of all digits.\n- `orchestrate_program_execution` ties everything together: it gets the user’s number, constructs the processor, computes the sum, and prints the result; any `ValueError` raised along the way is caught and reported, preventing crashes.\n\nFINAL SCORE:\n9/10  \nReason: The logic is correct, well-structured, and very readable; only minor stylistic simplifications (e.g., iterating directly over characters) could make it even more concise.\n\nENCOURAGEMENT:\nYou’re building clean, well-structured programs—keep refining this style and you’ll progress very quickly.','2026-04-09 14:38:00','CORRECT',98,0,1,78);
